Metcash Launches Ground Resistance Campaign to Fight Aldi Invasion
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA branches from an Aldi uprising in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground resistance campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares for the opening of two sales centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and event management, as well as e-marketing via social media.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands such as ice maker Simmo from Dunsborough, who distributes samples in IGA stores and store owners selling leased tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
It is expected that Metcash will release further details of its defense strategy on September 29, when the food, alcohol and equipment wholesaler is conducting its annual Investor Strategy Day.
There’s a lot at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the Eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will snatch around five percent of the food market in these two states twelve months after opening its first markets and will take away sales from all existing players, but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report published this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that next year Aldi will open 25 branches in SA and 30 in WA and generate revenues of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and grocery business and in the amounts on Metcash’s high fixed-cost basis could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash loses market shares in the Eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash’s turnover in the food and grocery business to fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017, and by 2.1 percent in 2018, reducing its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, senior fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to publicly respond to Mr. Douglass' comments.
But it is assumed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenues from Metcash’s food and food trade, which provides about 1,200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43 percent since 2012, resulting in operational debt reduction with simultaneous pressure on sales.
However, the wholesaler resists and invests more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week and improve IGA retailers in improving their stores by faster growing fresh foods and making a better choice for private customers.
Metcash CEO Ian Morrice says the price adjustments and store remediation programs will be added to Elan and hopes that the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
