And I think that Nick very quickly managed the ascent, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He climbs in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes, and he deserves all the criticism that he can get for it, but we're trying to support it for it, we're just trying to help him in it, we're trying to catch him
Europe’s refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes border, holds back refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and blocked the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday and detained all those who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border as hundreds of migrants gathered in a no-man’s-land and Serbian officials reacted with indignation.
The people who had fled violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations have increased.
As a police helicopter hovered over them, the migrants chanted "Open the border!" and shouted insults at the Hungarian police.
Some reject food and water from protest.
Serbia’s foreign minister said it was “unacceptable” that migrants would be sent back from Hungary, while more and more arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
Talks with Brussels and other countries must take place in the coming days," said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turbulence on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc at a controversial meeting in Brussels could not agree on a common immigration policy.
The ministers agreed, however, to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in crowded Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that the EU countries would take on a further 120,000 refugees, including some from the EU.
Federal Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called for a special European Union summit on Tuesday to discuss the continent’s immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not place its hopes on an immediate action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The state of emergency in two southern regions on Tuesday gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis, allowing them to block roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country was also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it ended a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were employed in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a significant bottleneck and entry point to the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most of the arrivals are economic refugees who are looking for a better life, and not war refugees who are entitled to protection – a view that strongly contradicts other EU countries, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make the crossing of the border or the damage to the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence that the government had built along the southern border with Serbia a crime. These laws also set higher levels of prison sentences.
"Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government declares a state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to formally approve the deployment of the military, which is expected next week, but reporters from the Associated Press have already seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, a state security adviser for Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border and 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They get over it by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train wagon with barbed wire had arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process the data of people and pressed a crowd to penetrate there.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway link from Serbia and Hungary and said they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
