This will happen if the Fed raises interest rates.
An increase in interest rates will come, and the rise will fluctuate, yields for bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into a recession.
We know that.
What we do not know is how long all this will last and how long it will last.
In particular, the history of the economy offers little guidance on how to proceed.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first interest rate increase and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial institutions react.
Therefore, representatives of the U.S. central bank have emphasized so strongly that investors should not focus on when they start raising interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants could find that the whole excitement may have been exaggerated due to an increase in interest rates.
“The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of ‘fair money’,” said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal heights, but still to a low level to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no effects.
Here’s a look at how some areas of the economy might react based on historical trends:
As the market has seen in the last month, anticipation of interest rate increases can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase occurs, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency that capital gains will be discarded 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the delay in monetary policy,” German bank analysts said in a recent study of what happens after the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
More precisely, in the past 35 years, the market management is mostly on the upward trend - about 14 percent - on the way to increase interest rates, quite flat in the 250 days thereafter (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to current gains at nuvets at a normal state of chess after 500 days.
The Deutsche Bank said that the impact on the shares tends to occur later in the rise cycle and returns are beginning to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often promote them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that it did not have before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is extremely noteworthy that the gross domestic product will be near its lowest point in the Fed’s interest rate hike.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 were only twice the nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to last and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes in such a fragile economic environment could be risky and raise the question “whether it’s different this time around,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been looking for an interest rate hike from the Fed all year round, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this meeting, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
"In our study, all of the increase cycles from 1950 to today took place in a super cycle with increasing fluctuations in GDP and pre-recession highs very quickly after the onset of recovery," the report said.
In contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an increase in interest rates, and the pattern is quite similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic price.
In the case of bonds, returns appear to change direction once the first increase/decrease occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will lead to yields falling closer between longer and shorter bonds, leading to a flattening of the curve.
High-interest bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, although “we’re still cautious about expecting higher returns,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that the markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of more stringent monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have expanded and volatility has increased – all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
On the whole, companies that do most of their business in the U.S. will benefit from it as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debt will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive on the global market and also financing their debts.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks tend to react extremely positively three months after an initial interest rate increase," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report to customers.
Firms with a strong balance sheet averaged 5 percentage points higher than firms with a weak balance sheet after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also outperformed their low quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percent) and 3 (percent).
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high proportion of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savings savers could see profits through higher returns, even if experts are of differing opinion on how quickly this will take place.
