At their most anticipated meeting in the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras-Mahagoni table to decide whether it’s time to raise the lead rate for the first time in almost a decade.
Threatening over them at one end of the decorated, two-storey meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the economic interests of the nation above all other things.
The central bank has a double mandate from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, the Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict, it will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to take off from the unprecedented stimulus by the near-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
While most data from the economy show it is growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could make precautionary Fed representatives anxious to amplify this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds — even if it’s only a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the most important thing they observe,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue waiting,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself insures the financial market.
About half of economists who were recently interviewed by Bloomberg have predicted an interest rate hike this week.
However, the financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator showing only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped by 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that the Fed policy would maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed would raise the rates at this point,” he said.
If she does, "she would have to go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so they don't panic."
Other experts argued that an interest rate hike would calm the financial markets because it would eliminate the uncertainty as to when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the recovery in the US.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that she expected an increase in the rate this year, despite complaints from Liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market was solid this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level seen by the Fed as full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And while inflation was constantly below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher interest rates and needs them because of labor market tensions,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world collapsed at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell more than 16% below its peak in May when investors feared a slowdown in China’s economy would shake global growth.
The market has recovered slightly this month, with the Dow now nearly 10% below the May high.
For the Fed representatives, the market turmoil influences the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news of the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would be pulling the trigger in this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, Senior Research Fellow at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former US employee.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to get the effects better under control.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impacts will be on the U.S. economy, and there is hardly any reliable data that describes developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere indication by then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “reinvent” its monetary expansion caused confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, Head of Global Asset Management Strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, remarked this month that "the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that are apparently unrelated to the fundamental economic data."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, which is committed to raising interest rates, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its lead rate by 0.75 percentage points in three meetings “despite limited noticeable impacts on growth in the United States,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed rescinded these cuts.
The Fed should only put aspects of financial stability first during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
Recent turbulences are not coming close to this level, he said.
“She certainly doesn’t want to get into a situation where she’s afraid of rising interest rates because the markets are excited,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I do not think it should be ahead of time.
