“Children increasingly come to these products, and unfortunately a percentage of them land on the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children intentionally drink disinfectants, while some do so to impress their friends or because of a test of courage on social media.
Videos on YouTube show how teenagers drink disinfectants just because of an inexpensive experience.
Adolescents have reportedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children may be attracted to attractive fragrances of disinfectants.
“A child doesn’t think this is bad for it,” Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand sanitizers) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scent, which are very appealing for children.
Hand sanitizers contain somewhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few sprays can lead to alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol," said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison call center at the University of Kansas Hospital, the Fox 4 transmitter in Kansas City.
So, you wouldn’t leave a sip of whisky around, but people leave these hand sanitizers within reach of children, and if children come to it, then it’s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four sprays of strawberry-scented hand disinfectant at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179 times higher than the threshold that is legally considered drunk in an adult, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency doctor who treated her at the Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah laughed at her words and was unable to walk when she arrived in the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma as the girl had fallen through the alcohol and hit her head, Ritchey said.
“It was very scary,” Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah’s mother, told CNN.
It could have been deadly for my child.
Lopez has recommended parents and teachers to use non-alcoholic products or disinfectant towels and to store hand sanitizers out of the reach of the child.
