EU wants to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish and thus give consumers a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which is presenting a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticized the plans: “Risks and side effects of misguided industrial and environmental policies are being passed on with full force to pregnant women and toddlers,” explains Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limit values of the nerve poison for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predators are already so heavily loaded with mercury that about 50 percent of the catches cannot be sold on the basis of the limit values still in force.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5% would remain unsold.
In return for this relief, the EU wants to increase limit values for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch, however, called this a “trick” because smaller fried fish, such as carp, are usually so low-loaded that they already meet the planned maximum values today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction manoeuvre that only helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Quecksilber is a highly toxic heavy metal that is highly enriched by the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause, especially in unborn, damage to the nervous system".
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment says on its homepage, with regard to the applicable maximum values, that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury is mainly brought into the environment by the burning of coal.
The German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tonnes of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written statement by the Federal Ministry of the Environment to the Greens-Bundestag Member of Parliament, Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube, was "permanent and extensively exceeded", the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings against mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.quecksilber-aktion.foodwatch.de
